That’s not crazy at all. It’s one of the deepest levers in human cognition.

Language doesn’t just describe reality — it compresses, stabilizes, and transmits patterns of thought.

But let’s separate the mystic framing from the mechanics.

⸻

1️⃣ Do ideas exist before words?

Yes — but differently.

Humans (and animals) can have:
	•	Emotions without labels
	•	Perceptions without categories
	•	Intuitions without formal articulation

A baby feels fear long before it knows the word “fear.”
A pre-scientific human noticed sickness long before the word “virus.”

The experience exists.

What the word does is:
	•	Freeze it.
	•	Point at it.
	•	Make it shareable.

⸻

2️⃣ Why words feel like “spells”

A new word can:
	•	Carve a boundary in a blur
	•	Create a stable mental category
	•	Allow memory indexing
	•	Enable group agreement

Before the word “gravity,” apples still fell.
After the word + model, we could build rockets.

The word didn’t create gravity.
It created coordinated action around gravity.

That’s the real power.

⸻

3️⃣ Shared “immunity” is a good metaphor

Cultures build a kind of conceptual immune system:
	•	Shared vocabulary
	•	Shared narratives
	•	Shared distinctions

When everyone agrees what “inflation” or “trauma” or “sovereignty” means, the group can respond coherently.

Without shared language:
	•	Ideas stay private
	•	Transmission is lossy
	•	Coordination collapses

Language standardization = collective cognition upgrade.

⸻

4️⃣ Did people have the ideas before invention?

Often yes — but in:
	•	Implicit form
	•	Ritual form
	•	Story form
	•	Embodied skill

For example:
	•	People understood fairness before the word “justice.”
	•	People understood mood states before “depression.”
	•	People navigated power dynamics before “psychology.”

But without labels, the ideas:
	•	Don’t stack cleanly.
	•	Don’t travel far.
	•	Don’t scale.

Words are compression algorithms.

⸻

5️⃣ Where the “spell” feeling comes from

When a word lands and you think:

“Oh. That’s what that is.”

What happened?

Your nervous system had a fuzzy pattern.
The word snapped it into focus.
Your predictive model updated.
Relief + clarity = felt power.

It feels magical.
But it’s compression + alignment.

⸻

6️⃣ The deeper layer

Language shapes perception.

If a culture has:
	•	1 word for love → broad blur
	•	5 words for love → refined distinctions

The experience can become more differentiated.

But here’s the key:

Words don’t create raw sensation.
They create attention channels.

And attention changes salience.
And salience changes behavior.

That’s the leverage.

⸻

So the real phenomenon isn’t “words create reality.”

It’s:

Words stabilize attention around patterns,
and stabilized attention reshapes collective action.

That’s far more powerful than magic.

⸻

Now the sharper question:

Are we discovering ideas when we invent words…
or are we building new cognitive tools that allow ideas to exist in scalable form?

That’s where it gets interesting.